
# Zeek::TrafficReceiver

This plugin provides native TrafficReceiver support for Zeek. 


## Installation


### Package Manager

The plugin is available as package for the [Zeek Package Manager](https://github.com/zeek/package-manager) and can be installed using the following command:

    zkg install zeek-trafficreceiver

### Manual Install

The following will compile and install the TrafficReceiver plugin alongside Zeek:

    # ./configure && make && make install

If everything built and installed correctly, you should see this:

    # zeek -NN Zeek::TrafficReceiver
    Zeek::TrafficReceiver - Packet acquisition via TrafficReceiver (dynamic, version 1.0.0)
    [Packet Source] TrafficReceiverReader (interface prefix "trafficreceiver"; supports live input)
    [Constant] TrafficReceiver::buffer_size

## Usage

Once installed, you can use TrafficReceiver interfaces/ports by prefixing them with `trafficreceiver::` on the command line. For example, to use TrafficReceiver to use a local socket with port 57012:

    # zeek -i trafficreceiver::127.0.0.1:57012

## Usage with `zeekctl`

You can use the TrafficReceiver plugin with `zeekctl`. The following shows a sample configuration:

```
    [manager]
    type=manager
    host=localhost
     
    [proxy-1]
    type=proxy
    host=localhost
     
    [worker-1]
    type=worker
    host=localhost
    interface=trafficreceiver::1.2.3.4:57012
    # Optional parameters for per node configuration:
    trafficreceiver_buffer_size=32*1024

    [worker-2]
    type=worker
    host=localhost
    interface=trafficreceiver::1.2.3.5:57012
    # Optional parameters for per node configuration:
    trafficreceiver_buffer_size=32*1024
```

Note that workers must consume different streams (different IP, Port combinations). The TrafficReceiver plugin does not yet support multiple workers consuming the *same* stream.

## Debugging the Plugin

To debug the plugin, configure with `--enable-debug`, as well as Zeek itself.  Then when you run Zeek, add `-B plugin-Zeek-TrafficReceiver` to the command line to enable debugging.  The resulting `debug.log` should show debug comments.

## Advanced Configuration

While the plugin aims at providing a "plug and play" user experience, it exposes at the momement one option of the underlying API for customization (see [init.zeek](scripts/init.zeek) for the default values):

* `buffer_size`: Set the overall buffer size allocated per socket. 